---
import ChapterShell from "../../../components/ChapterShell.astro";
import { localePath } from "../../../lib/i18n";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import DiagramFigure from "../../../components/diagrams/DiagramFigure.astro";
import SelfCheckKeystone from "../../../components/diagrams/SelfCheckKeystone.astro";
import RepairBudgetFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/RepairBudgetFlow.astro";
import AuthoritySplitFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/AuthoritySplitFlow.astro";
import PlanThenEvidenceFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/PlanThenEvidenceFlow.astro";
import SemanticCompletionFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/SemanticCompletionFlow.astro";
import PlanAuditRiskFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/PlanAuditRiskFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="05" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      How can Maka let an Agent inspect its own work, find gaps, and attempt repair — without letting
      “I checked” become self-authorization? Not by asking the model “are you sure?”, but by organizing
      Self-check as a planned, public-evidence, hygiene-aware, durable, repair-capped feedback loop. Key
      line:
      <strong>Self-check can produce evidence and feedback; it cannot manufacture trust.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§05 · Scene"
    title="Start from “I already checked”"
    lede="Free reflection restates intent; unbounded check–repair becomes a second Agent loop without budget."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the Agent finishes a complex migration and replies “done — the code should work.” That
      sentence has almost no engineering value. It does not answer: which final artifacts were checked,
      which public commands ran, what exit codes were, whether temp output stayed in scratch, whether
      the final workspace was polluted, whether new files were planned deliverables or accidents,
      whether evidence came only from public task material, or how many repairs are allowed after
      failure.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull">
      How do we give the model a chance to find its own mistakes, while putting self-check inputs,
      evidence, side effects, and retry counts into a protocol the Runtime can inspect?
    </blockquote>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§05 · Keystone"
    title="Self-check is a Feedback Plane, not an Authority Plane"
    lede="Model reports; Runtime admits, audits, and bounds."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · Plan → Evidence → Source Guard → Semantic gate → bounded repair; the model cannot decide infinite self-proof."
      alt="Five-step feedback plane: Plan, Evidence, Source Guard, Semantic gate, Bounded repair; invariant: Self-check cannot manufacture trust."
    >
      <SelfCheckKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Self-check Plan</strong> — what to check and where temp output goes (model submits; Runtime admits)</li>
      <li><strong>Public Evidence</strong> — what was actually run or observed (with source refs)</li>
      <li><strong>Source Guard</strong> — whether strings cite only public task material (deterministic policy)</li>
      <li><strong>Hygiene / Consistency Audit</strong> — scratch escape and unplanned side effects</li>
      <li><strong>Repair Gate</strong> — whether one extra check/repair Turn is allowed (hard cap)</li>
    </ul>
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · Model reports · Runtime admits · official truth lives elsewhere."
      alt="Three columns: Model advisory, Runtime gates, Authority elsewhere."
    >
      <AuthoritySplitFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="plan"
    label="§05 · Plan"
    title="Why a Self-check Plan must come first"
    lede="Checks produce side effects; post-hoc rationalization cannot substitute for a prior plan."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · Plan submit → Runtime admit → Evidence submit → Strong pass?; missing plan can block a strong pass."
      alt="Four steps: Plan submit, Runtime admit, Evidence submit, Strong pass."
    >
      <PlanThenEvidenceFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      Compiles write object files; scripts may overwrite deliverables; even a “verification output” can
      change the workspace listing. If the Agent only explains “those files were temporary” after the
      check, Runtime cannot tell prior plan from after-the-fact story. Hence
      <code>self_check_plan_submit</code> declares three groups:
    </p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>finalArtifacts</strong> (at least one) — <code>path</code> / <code>purpose</code> /
        <code>publicReason</code>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>selfCheckScratch</strong> — scratch root, optional expected generated paths, public
        reason (gate prompts often recommend <code>/tmp/maka-self-check/...</code>)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>workspaceGuardPlan</strong> — which paths will be checked, which additions are expected,
        which generated paths may appear outside scratch, and why that fits the task
      </li>
    </ul>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Plan as audit baseline">observed change
  → compare with accepted plan
  → planned final artifact, expected output, or unexplained side effect?</pre>
    <p>
      Without a plan, facts may still be recorded into Task Events, but the strong-pass gate blocks with
      <code>missing_self_check_plan</code> — the tool layer may record; the gate decides whether semantic
      completion is supported (deferred enforcement).
    </p>
    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">History aside</p>
      <p>
        Self-check architecture chapter:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/774")}>maka:pr:774</a>. Later freshness tightening:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/954")}>maka:pr:954</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="schema"
    label="§05 · Schema"
    title="Make Self-check a bounded object first"
    lede="Schema solves persistability and prompt safety; it alone does not prove evidence authenticity."
  >
    <p>Current <code>self_check_submit</code> is not free text. Requirements include:</p>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><code>status</code> is only <code>pass / fail / inconclusive</code></li>
      <li><code>publicReason</code> non-empty, ≤ 2,000 characters</li>
      <li>at least one command or artifact evidence item</li>
      <li>command ≤ 1,000 chars; output excerpt ≤ 2,000 chars</li>
      <li>≤ 25 command and ≤ 25 artifact evidence items; ≤ 20 artifact refs</li>
      <li>path ≤ 500 chars; metadata ≤ 30 keys, depth depth ≤ 3, string values ≤ 500</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Command evidence may carry <code>command</code> / <code>exitCode?</code> / <code>timedOut?</code> /
      <code>outputExcerpt?</code> / <code>artifactRefs?</code>. Artifact evidence may carry
      <code>path</code> / <code>kind</code> / <code>exists?</code> / <code>sizeBytes?</code> /
      <code>hash?</code> / bounded metadata. Fields are mostly model-submitted via tool args — schema
      blocks unbounded payloads, but does not by itself prove a command ran or a hash matches current
      bytes.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="guard"
    label="§05 · Source Guard"
    title="What may enter the feedback loop"
    lede="A lexical admission filter — not an access-control system, and not a complete information-flow proof."
  >
    <p>
      <code>validateHeavyTaskPublicStrings()</code> walks nearly every string in plan and Self-check:
      reason, command, output excerpt, artifact path, metadata, scratch path, workspace-guard commands,
      and side-effect paths. Known lexical categories reject material such as: hidden tests /
      references / artifacts; private thresholds or scoring criteria; raw assertion-derived
      expected/actual; evaluator-only files; private/official execution details; private benchmark
      identifiers.
    </p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Source Guard result">HeavyTaskSourceGuardResult
  status: accepted | rejected
  checkedAt
  categories[]
  publicReason</pre>
    <p>
      The recorder appends <code>heavy_task_self_check_plan_recorded</code> or
      <code>heavy_task_self_check_recorded</code> only when the guard accepts. Projection re-runs
      <code>isAcceptedHeavyTaskSelfCheck()</code>; old states that no longer pass the public guard are
      ignored with a warning. The guard cannot stop an Agent that already has overly broad Tool access
      from reading private files — isolation and tool exposure must be solved at earlier boundaries.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="hygiene"
    label="§05 · Hygiene"
    title="Execution Hygiene and Plan Consistency Audit"
    lede="Check side effects are part of the protocol; planned artifacts ≠ accidental changes."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · Plan-audit risks: missing plan / unplanned path / scratch escape block strong pass; planned artifact is diagnostic only."
      alt="Four-column risk matrix: missing plan, unplanned path, scratch escape, planned artifact."
    >
      <PlanAuditRiskFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      <code>executionHygiene</code> reports sandbox root / strategy, cleanup,
      <code>workspaceSideEffects</code> (<code>none | cleaned | present | unknown</code>), and workspace
      guard (checked paths, before/after listing, added/modified/removed). Strong pass requires a
      sandbox root and <code>workspaceGuard.checked === true</code>; non-empty
      <code>remainingSideEffectPaths</code> always blocks. These fields are still mostly model-submitted
      today — Runtime runs a consistency audit; it must not be treated as executor-signed filesystem
      truth.
    </p>
    <p>
      Main risk flags from <code>auditSelfCheckPlanConsistency()</code>:
      <code>missing_self_check_plan</code> (blocks),
      <code>planned_final_artifact_added</code> (does not block; diagnostic),
      <code>unplanned_added_path</code> (blocks),
      <code>scratch_escape</code> (blocks). Final artifacts are supposed to appear — not every workspace
      delta is pollution — but “I happened to create a new file” does not automatically become a final
      artifact. The difference is whether the plan came first and declared the path.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="observation"
    label="§05 · Observation"
    title="Machine Workspace Observation is neutral corroboration"
    lede="A diagnostic listing — not a full workspace attestation."
  >
    <p>
      Before the first gate evaluation, <code>TaskAgentController</code> may call
      <code>observeHeavyTaskWorkspace()</code>: only with an isolated executor; roots from accepted-plan
      final-artifact parents and Self-check checked paths; only <code>/app/...</code>; ≤ 12 roots; one
      listing level per root; 30s command timeout; recorded as
      <code>heavy_task_workspace_observation_recorded</code> with <code>source.kind=system</code>. It does
      not read file bodies or compute a full manifest/hash. Today it does not alone block an otherwise
      satisfying pass — diagnostic, not full attestation.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="semantic"
    label="§05 · Semantic"
    title="Semantic completion needs many conditions at once"
    lede="status=pass is only one item; the final status always carries advisory=true."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 5 · Semantic-complete protocol: accepted pass → sandbox/guard → plan audit → todos/phase gates; any blocker → incomplete."
      alt="Four gates feed semantic complete, labeled advisory=true."
    >
      <SemanticCompletionFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      <code>evaluateHeavyTaskCompletionStatus()</code> yields semantic complete only when all of the
      following hold (teaching enumeration):
    </p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Heavy-task mode enabled</li>
      <li>Latest accepted public Self-check exists with status <code>pass</code></li>
      <li>Sandbox execution evidence present; workspace guard executed</li>
      <li>No uncleared or unplanned blocking workspace delta; plan consistent with evidence</li>
      <li>Non-empty latest todos; all completed, or cancelled with nonblocking evidence</li>
      <li>
        Early phase-gate todos <code>runnable_artifact</code> and <code>public_check</code> both completed
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      The gate derives an Acceptance Checklist from visible contracts (final artifacts, parse hints,
      phase-gate todos, hygiene requirements) rather than inventing a hard contract from fragile NL
      heuristics. Known limitation of required-artifact address checks: with multiple final artifacts,
      hitting <strong>at least one</strong> path/basename in evidence text is enough — not yet
      per-check all coverage (Target).
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="repair"
    label="§05 · Repair"
    title="Bounded repair: allow correction, forbid infinite self-loops"
    lede="maxRepairAttempts is fixed at 1; repair is a new Turn inside the same Attempt, not a new Task Attempt."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 6 · Gate fails → check repair budget → bounded Repair Turn → re-check; stop when the budget is spent."
      alt="Five steps: Gate fails, Budget check, Repair Turn, Re-check, Stop loop."
    >
      <RepairBudgetFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      <code>evaluateHeavyTaskSelfCheckGate()</code> yields
      <code>allow</code> / <code>repair</code> / <code>cap reached</code>. Current
      <code>TaskAgentController</code> sequence:
    </p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Main Invocation ends</li>
      <li>Record machine workspace observation</li>
      <li>Evaluate gate; append <code>heavy_task_self_check_gate_recorded</code></li>
      <li>
        If action=repair: create a new Turn/AgentRun on the same Session / workspace; prompt includes
        blocker, checklist, latest Self-check summary, and machine observation
      </li>
      <li>After the repair Turn, observe and gate again; repairAttemptsUsed=1 — no third Turn</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Accepted plan / Self-check become Task Events, project to
      <code>latestHeavyTaskSelfCheckPlan</code> / <code>latestHeavyTaskSelfCheck</code>, and enter the
      bounded compact-evidence window (later Attempts typically render ~5 command and ~5 artifact
      evidence items). Old Self-checks are not mutated — a new event only changes the latest
      projection.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="failure"
    label="§05 · Failure"
    title="Missing evidence should lower confidence, not invent facts"
    lede="Fail closed on admission; fail open on inventing success."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Invalid plan schema → validation error; no accepted plan; never “the model probably meant the same.”</li>
      <li>Source guard rejected → no accepted Self-check append; sensitive content did not become public feedback.</li>
      <li>No evidence → schema rejects; a <code>pass</code> string alone is not evidence.</li>
      <li><code>fail/inconclusive</code> → semantic incomplete; may trigger one repair; need not fake pass.</li>
      <li>Missing sandbox/guard, unplanned path, or scratch escape → strong pass blocked.</li>
      <li>Machine observation failure → store error excerpt; observation failure ≠ workspace clean.</li>
      <li>Still incomplete after repair → record final gate state; no infinite repair.</li>
      <li>Replayed Self-check fails public revalidation → projection ignores it with a warning.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="stub">
      <p class="stub__tag">Current trust boundary</p>
      <p>
        Model-reported evidence is not yet executor-attested; freshness high water is missing (a
        Write/Edit after Self-check may leave an old pass as latest); observation is one directory
        level; source guard is a known-pattern set; artifact coverage is any, not all. Target:
        RuntimeEvent/artifact-linked observations, workspace manifest diffs, per-check coverage,
        mutation-stale conclusions, versioned repair policy (hard cap still Runtime-enforced).
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="not"
    label="§05 · Not"
    title="What Self-check is not"
    lede="Draw the boundary so feedback is not sold as authority, an infinite loop, or workspace rollback."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li><strong>Not “think again”</strong> — reflection without plan / evidence / hygiene is not an accepted Self-check.</li>
      <li><strong>Not a hidden information channel</strong> — only public task-derived facts.</li>
      <li><strong>Not an infinite repair loop</strong> — at most one extra repair Turn today.</li>
      <li><strong>Not workspace rollback</strong> — audit can surface side effects; it cannot restore files.</li>
      <li><strong>Not the final source of truth</strong> — always advisory; RuntimeEvents / Tool Results / Task Events / artifacts keep their own boundaries (back-links to §02 / §06).</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="figure-note">
      Invariants: Plan precedes trust; Evidence required; Public-only admission; Append before project;
      Advisory forever; Hygiene is part of the check; Planned ≠ accidental; Repair is bounded; Machine
      facts stay neutral; Invalid states remain observable.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <div slot="outline">
    <ul class="outline-list">
      <li>Keystone + plan/schema/guard/hygiene + semantic gates + repair cap=1</li>
      <li>Plan-audit risk matrix and semantic-completion protocol figures</li>
      <li>History asides <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/774")}>maka:pr:774</a> ·
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/954")}>maka:pr:954</a></li>
      <li>Current advisory vs Target executor-owned high-water evidence written (CN+EN ship together)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</ChapterShell>

